<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Great Alpine Road</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Great Alpine Road</h2><p><i>Victoria, Australia · B500, Wangaratta to Bairnsdale via Mount Hotham</i></p><p><b>Australia's highest sealed road — 339 km from wine country over a 1,845 m alpine pass to Gippsland.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>244 km (152 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>5–6 hrs no stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>December–April for full open road; ski season (Jun–Sept) requires chains; closures possible</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Snow and ice in winter; chains required Jun–Oct above Harrietville; wombats and roos at dawn/dusk; fog</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>471</td></tr></table><hr><p>The highest year-round sealed road in Australia. Starts in Wangaratta in the Ovens Valley wine country, climbs through Bright (a tobacco town turned tourist village), past the old gold workings of Harrietville, then up to Mount Hotham (1,861 m), one of Australia's main ski resorts. From Hotham the road traverses a high tussock-grassland plateau before descending to Omeo and the rolling pastures of Gippsland. The alpine ash forests on the climb are some of the world's tallest flowering plants — Eucalyptus regnans to 90 m. Fires in 2003, 2009 (Black Saturday), and 2019–20 (Black Summer) burnt much of this country; you'll see standing dead trees and vigorous regrowth in alternating bands.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Bright</b> — Autumn-foliage town in the Ovens Valley — European trees planted by gold miners turn flame orange in late April / early May. Wandiligong heritage village nearby.</li><li><b>Harrietville</b> — Last village before the climb. 1850s gold-rush bones still visible — old sluice channels in the river. Mount Feathertop (Victoria's second-highest peak) rises behind.</li><li><b>Mount Hotham</b> — Australia's third-highest ski resort (1,861 m village; 1,861 m highest sealed point on the road just east of the village). Year-round restaurants; alpine wildflowers in December.</li><li><b>Dinner Plain</b> — Architect-designed alpine village (1986) of corrugated-iron and timber lodges in vernacular styling. Cross-country skiing in winter, mountain biking in summer.</li><li><b>Omeo</b> — Old gold-rush town at 690 m. Once isolated for months by snow each year. The road from Omeo down to the coast is one of Victoria's quietest drives.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
